text: Total Synthesis of Rishirilide B by Organocatalytic Oxidative Kinetic Resolution: Revision of Absolute Configuration of (+)-Rishirilide B Minami Odagi,* Kota Furukori, Kan Takayama, Keiichi Noguchi, and Kazuo Nagasawa* Dedicated to Professor Yoshito Kishi on the occasion of his 80th birthday Abstract: Described herein is the enantioselective syntheses of (+)- and ((cid:2))-rishirilide B from the corresponding optically active b-substituted tetralones, which were obtained by oxida- tive kinetic resolution based on a-hydroxylation in the presence of a chiral guanidine-bisurea bifunctional organocatalyst. Benzylic oxidation of the tetralones at C1 followed by regioselective isomerization of the oxabenzonorbornadiene structure led to rishirilide B. Our findings lead to the revision of the previously proposed (2R,3R,4R) absolute configuration of (+)-rishirilide B to (2S,3S,4S). ((cid:2))-Rishirilide A (1) and (+)-rishirilide B [(+)-2] are anthracenone-type natural products isolated from Streptomy- ces rishiriensis OFR-1056 in 1984 (Figure 1),[1] and were subsequently found in Streptomyces bottropensis.[2] (+)-Rish- Figure 1. Structures of rishirilides A (1) and B (2). irilide B [(+)-2] has moderate inhibitory activities against a2- macroglobulin, glutathione S-transferase, and asparaginyl- tRNA synthetase,[3, 4] which play roles in thrombosis and cancer. Key structural features of the rishirilides include three or four consecutive stereogenic centers involving quaternary carbon centers on the A ring. Both groups used similar strategies for constructing the B ring in 2 by connecting a highly functionalized A ring to the C ring (Scheme 1). Although these approaches are efficient, construction of the consecutive stereogenic centers in the A ring is still a challenge. We recently developed an oxidative kinetic resolution reaction to obtain chiral b-substituted 1- tetralones,[10, 11] and we planned to use this in an alternative strategy for the synthesis of (2R,3R,4R)-2 as depicted in Scheme 2. We envisioned that (2R,3R,4R)-2 could be synthe- Scheme 2. Synthetic plan for (2R,3R,4R)-rishirilide B [(2R,3R,4R)-2]. PMB = para-methoxybenzyl. sized from the oxabenzonorbornadiene 11 by regioselective isomerization. Construction of the oxabenzonorbornadiene moiety corresponding to the C ring could be achieved by a Diels–Alder reaction of the AB ring with furan.[12] The benzyne 12’ would be generated from the bromo triflate 12, which can be obtained from the a-hydroxy-b-keto ester ((cid:2))- 13 by diastereoselective introduction of the isoamyl moiety at C4 and benzylic oxidation at C1. Asymmetric synthesis of ((cid:2))-13 was planned by organocatalytic oxidative kinetic resolution of the b-keto ester rac-14.[10]

Our synthesis commenced with an asymmetric synthesis of ((cid:2))-13 from rac-14, which was synthesized from commer- steps 4-hydroxybenzaldehyde cially (Scheme 3).[13] Oxidative kinetic resolution of rac-14, bearing a para-methoxybenzyl group on the phenolic hydroxy group, was examined in the presence of a catalytic amount of (R,R)- 15 (2 mol %). Under the previously developed reaction conditions,[10] kinetic resolution took place smoothly, and ((cid:2))-13 was obtained in 48 % yield with 90 % ee, together with (+)-14 in 50 % yield with 86 % ee (s = 53).[14] The enantio- meric excess of ((cid:2))-13 was increased to 99 % ee after a single recrystallization.[15] Then, ((cid:2))-13 was reacted with isoamyl magnesium bromide to afford 16, in 91 % yield, as a single diastereomer, whose relative configuration was confirmed by nOe experiments. In this reaction, the newly generated the stereocenter at C4 was controlled by approach of (cid:2) 2017 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. Grignard reagent from the sterically less hindered axial orientation to the ketone in ((cid:2))-13. Then, the PMB group in 16 was removed by treatment with DDQ to give 17, which was subsequently reacted with triflic anhydride in the presence of triethylamine to give 18 in 76 % yield. With 19 in hand, oxidation at C1 was carried out with FeCl3·6 H2O in the presence of KMnO4.[16] This oxidation proceeded smoothly, thus affording the ketone 12 in 85 % yield. The absolute configurations in 12 were confirmed to be (2R,3R,4R) by X- ray crystallographic analysis of 19, which was obtained from the triflate moiety with potassium 12 by hydrolysis of carbonate in methanol.[17] Then, construction of the C ring by a Diels–Alder reaction with 12 and furan was carried out. Thus, 12 was treated with nBuLi in the presence of furan, and the Diels–Alder reaction took place smoothly to construct the oxabenzonorbornadiene skeleton, thus affording 11 in 81 % yield (d.r. = 1:1).

Next, regioselective isomerization of the oxabenzonor- bornadiene moiety in 11 was examined under acidic con- ditions (Table 1). We initially examined Brønsted acids, hydrochloric acid, and para-toluenesulfonic acid (entries 1 and 2). In these cases either low yields of the isomerization products 20 and 21 or decomposition products of 11 were obtained. Next, Lewis-acid-promoted isomerization was investigated. In the case of tin(IV) chloride, the yield of the isomerization products was slightly increased to 38 %, but the selectivity was poor (entry 4). In contrast, selectivity was increased with boron tribromide, and 20 was obtained in 46 % yield as the major product in 6:1 regioisomeric ratio (entry 7). The compound 20 was obtained in 72 % yield when diiso- propyl ether (5 equiv) was added to control the excessive Lewis acidity of boron tribromide (entry 8).[18] In this isomer- ization reaction of 11, two possible transition states, TS-1 and TS-2, should be considered. TS-1 has less electronic repulsion compared to TS-2 (C8 and C10a versus C5 and C10a), and the phenol 20 was generated predominantly via TS-1 (Scheme 3). Finally, synthesis of (2R,3R,4R)-2 was accomplished by the tert-butyl group in 20 with aluminium removal of trichloride in 95 % yield. [a] Yield of a mixture of 20 and 21. However, to our surprise, the optical rotation of our synthetic (2R,3R,4R)-2 was (cid:2)14.8 (c = 0.27, EtOH), that is, having the opposite sign to that of the natural product, and in conflict with previous synthetic studies.[7, 8] Therefore, we compared the spectral and rotation data, and HPLC retention time, of our synthetic (2R,3R,4R)-2 with those of natural (+)-2, which was kindly provided by Professor Dr. Becht- hold.[2] The 1H NMR spectrum of our synthetic (2R,3R,4R)-2 matched that of natural (+)-2, but the optical rotation of the (cid:3)25 D ¼ + 46.7 (c 0.03, EtOH)], natural product had a plus sign [ a½ and the HPLC retention time of natural (+)-2 (t = 8.3 min) was different from that of our synthetic (2R,3R,4R)-2 (t = 11.2 min) on a chiral-phase column (Figure 2 a and b). In view of these observations, we decided to synthesize (2S,3S,4S)-2 from (+)-14 (86 % ee), which was obtained from the oxidative kinetic resolution reaction of rac-14 (Scheme 3). addition, the retention time on the chiral-phase HPLC of synthetic (2S,3S,4S)-2 was in good accordance with that of natural (+)-2 (Figures 2 a and c). These findings demonstrate that the absolute configurations of natural (+)-2 are not (2R,3R,4R) as previously proposed, but must be corrected to (2S,3S,4S).[19] A possible explanation of the misleading sign of the optical rotations reported by the other groups would be the presence of impurities, most likely formed in the final step.[20] In conclusion, we have achieved asymmetric total syn- theses of both (2R,3R,4R)-rishirilide B [(2R,3R,4R)-2] and (2S,3S,4S)-rishirilide B [(2S,3S,4S)-2] by means of a strategy featuring 1) oxidative kinetic resolution of the b-substituted tetralone rac-14, in the presence of the guanidine-bisurea bifunctional organocatalyst (R,R)-15, to construct the stereo- centers at C2 and C3, and 2) regioselective isomerization of oxabenzonorbornadiene to construct the C ring. Detailed comparison of the natural and synthetic products established that the previously proposed (2R,3R,4R) absolute configu- ration of natural (+)-rishirilide B [(+)-2] is not correct, and should be revised to (2S,3S,4S). We believe the kinetic resolution strategy will also be a powerful tool for determin- ing the configuration of other natural products on the basis of synthetic studies.
